            "summary": "SLE: Flood - 09-2024 -  Floods",
            "description": "<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-GB;\">There has been reported cases of multiple disaster incident in Freetown and several part of the country between late August and September 2024. According to the National Disaster management Agency ( NDMA), the Bumbuna Dam in Tonkolili district, overflowed beyond its capacity due to persistent heavy downpour of rain on 16<sup>th</sup> September 2024. This incident resulted in severe flooding in communities downstream&nbsp; and displaced 747 people, loss of household items, food supplies and <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>livelihoods (livestock, farmlands <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>and crops). Also, the stagnant floodwaters affected WASH facilities thus posing risk to cholera, typhoid and malaria.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-GB;\">Similarly, NDMA has reported flooding incidents from seven other districts (Kambia,&nbsp;<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>Port Loko, Moyamba, Bonthe, Kailahun, Pujehun and Bombali districts). Over 1,500 farmers have seen their farmlands submerged, with crops either destroyed or severely damaged, loss of&nbsp;properties, livelihoods and displacement<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp; </span>in over 50 communities. This has threatened not only their current food supply but also their long-term income and ability to recover after the floods.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto; line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: 'Times New Roman'; mso-fareast-language: EN-GB;\">Sierra Leone has recently recorded frequent infrastructure collapse in the western area. On September 16, whiles the Red Cross, Goverment and other partners are busy planing and evacuating the dam victims a seven storey building in the east- end of Freetown ( Shell, Kissy) collapsed and destroyed nearby buildings. As at today the search and rescure teams have recorded 15 deaths, 8 injuries and it is estimated that people are still trapped under the rubble.&nbsp;</span></p>",
            "translation_module_original_language": "en"
          }
        ],
